AGI - Sunday, March 30th will be the World Day on Bipolar Disorder >, on the day of Vincent van Gogh's birth which is believed to have been affection both in comorbidity with other mental disorders. But today the problem is to improve the ability to identify pathology early: about 70% of affected people received a wrong diagnosis and 30% of these even for several times. >
<br> Often considered 'glamour', associated with creativity, fantasy and estro, > from which the phenomenon 'I want to be bipolar', practically a 'stigma to the contrary, bipolar disorder is actually a severe and recurrent pathology, capable of compromising the quality of life > and the psychosocial sphere of those suffering it. Today it affects more than one million and 200 thousand Italians, between 1 and 2% of the general population, with a slightly greater prevalence in women and a more frequent occurrence between 15 and 30 years. But it is an underestimation, the tip of an iceberg of a complex disorder, whose symptoms are often similar to those of other mental disorders, such as depression and schizophrenia.
It should not be surprising, therefore, if late or incorrect diagnosis are very common: about 70% of the affected people received a wrong diagnosis and of these 30% even for several times. Before the diagnosis and the beginning of the treatment, about eight years after the beginning. The Italian Society of Psychiatry calls attention to the importance of early diagnosis and correct therapeutic management, as well as to the need to break down the stigma that still weighs on this disease.&nbsp;
"It is a disorder that involves significant impairment, sometimes extreme, not only in mood, but also in the cognitive sphere, volitive and neurovegetative > and that can have an important impact, and in some cases devastating, on the daily life of those suffering and the people close to him - says Prof. Liliana Dell'Osso, president of the Italian Society of Psychiatry -. The bipolar disorder is characterized by episodes of mania or hypomania> alternating with phases of depression, which can affect the ability to function, the management of emotions and social relations. Despite the widespread spread, bipolar disorder is often misunderstood, and many people with this condition also face the weight of social stigma." >
<br The bipolar disorder also exposes those suffering from additional risks, as it is often not correctly recognized and framed, sometimes mistaken for a unipolar depressive disorder. "Slighter hypomaniacal phases can in fact escape the anamnestic collection, because the patient - interpreting them as periods of particular well-being - does not report them not recognizing the pathological nature or not accepting the diagnosis of bipolar disorder, which is associated in some cases with a major stigma - the president SIP - states. In addition, in general we do not forget that the disorders of which the brain may suffer must be considered with maximum attention, as for any other organ of our body: the result of a non-treatment can also be fatal, in relation to the suicidal risk." >
<br> "Premature diagnosis and therapeutic intervention are fundamental to improve the course of the disease, reducing its impact on the quality of life of those suffering from it - says Antonio Vita, SIP Vice President and professor of psychiatry at the University of Brescia -. It is necessary to listen carefully to patients and to make an accurate anamnesi>, also with the help of family members, to avoid prescribing inadequate therapies that can worsen the situation instead of improving it. The risks of a diagnostic error > may be important, both because the treatment may vary considerably, both because it could maintain a poor awareness of the pathology by patients and family members. Today we have medicines aimed mainly at stabilizing mood, which are well established in clinical practice and which aim to reduce or disappear the occurrence of depressive and/or hypo/maniacal episodes, >cosis' as psychosocial treatments of proven effectiveness, which are in any case prescribed and monitored in the specialist field. Research is also very active especially in the direction of a more accurate clinical and biological characterization of the disorder for the best personalization of care". &nbsp;

